Storage Classes in C language:

i)   auto      --> for local variable
ii)  register  --> for local variable
iii) static    --> for both global and local variable
iv)  extern    --> for both global and local variable

Local variables --> declared inside a function or a block (like main(), if, for,etc)
Global variable --> declared outside of all functions, usually at the top of the program

i) auto storage class
   Storage - stack
   Initial value - garbage
   Scope - within block
   Life time - end of the block

   Note: auto is only used for local variables and this is the default class for local variables

ii) register storage class
    Storage - register
    Initial value - garbage
    Scope - within block
    Life time - end of the block

    Note: this is just a suggestion to the compiler to store the variable in the register it is not a
          compulsion to it. so it may store it in the register it is not compulsory


iii) static storage class
     Storage - static memory
     Initial value - zero
     Scope - within block
     Life time - till end of the program

iv) extern storage class
    Storage - static memory
    Initial value - zero
    Scope - global
    Life time - till end of the program

